            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the photoelectric effect calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool implements Einstein’s photoelectric equation to relate
                the energy of incoming photons to the work function of a metal
                and the kinetic energy of emitted electrons. It lets you work
                with either wavelength or frequency and supports a library of
                common metals with typical work functions.
              </p>

              <h3>Key equations</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Photon energy</strong></p>
                <p>\( E = h f = \dfrac{h c}{\lambda} \)</p>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(E\) = photon energy (J)</li>
                  <li>
                    \(h = 6.62607015\times10^{-34}\,\text{J·s}\) (Planck’s
                    constant)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    \(c = 2.99792458\times10^{8}\,\text{m/s}\) (speed of light)
                  </li>
                  <li>\(f\) = frequency (Hz)</li>
                  <li>\(\lambda\) = wavelength (m)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Einstein’s photoelectric equation</strong></p>
                <p>\( K_{\max} = h f - \phi \)</p>
                <p>or, in electronvolts:</p>
                <p>
                  \( K_{\max}(\text{eV}) = E_{\text{photon}}(\text{eV}) -
                  \phi(\text{eV}) \)
                </p>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    \(K_{\max}\) = maximum kinetic energy of emitted electrons
                  </li>
                  <li>\(\phi\) = work function of the metal</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Threshold frequency and wavelength</strong></p>
                <p>\( f_0 = \dfrac{\phi}{h} \)</p>
                <p>\( \lambda_0 = \dfrac{c}{f_0} = \dfrac{h c}{\phi} \)</p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Stopping potential and electron speed</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( e V_s = K_{\max} \Rightarrow V_s = \dfrac{K_{\max}}{e} \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( K_{\max} = \dfrac{1}{2} m_e v_{\max}^2 \Rightarrow v_{\max}
                  = \sqrt{\dfrac{2 K_{\max}}{m_e}} \)
                </p>
                <p>with:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    \(e = 1.602176634\times10^{-19}\,\text{C}\) (elementary
                    charge)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    \(m_e = 9.10938356\times10^{-31}\,\text{kg}\) (electron
                    mass)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>Step-by-step: from wavelength to stopping potential</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>Convert the input wavelength to meters (if needed).</li>
                <li>
                  Compute the frequency using \( f = c / \lambda \) (unless you
                  directly entered \(f\)).
                </li>
                <li>Compute photon energy \(E = h f\).</li>
                <li>
                  Convert the work function \(\phi\) to joules if it was given
                  in eV.
                </li>
                <li>Apply Einstein’s equation \(K_{\max} = h f - \phi\).</li>
                <li>If \(K_{\max} \le 0\), no electrons are emitted.</li>
                <li>
                  Otherwise, compute:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Stopping potential \(V_s = K_{\max} / e\)</li>
                    <li>
                      Maximum speed \(v_{\max} = \sqrt{2 K_{\max} / m_e}\)
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ol>

