              <h3>Conceptual notes for students</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Intensity vs. frequency:</strong> Increasing intensity
                  at fixed frequency increases the number of emitted electrons
                  (current), but not their maximum kinetic energy.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Instantaneous emission:</strong> As soon as light with
                  \(f \ge f_0\) hits the surface, electrons are emitted without
                  measurable delay.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Evidence for photons:</strong> The linear relation
                  between \(K_{\max}\) and \(f\) with slope \(h\) is one of the
                  classic confirmations of the photon model of light.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>What units does this calculator use?</h3>
              <p>
                You can enter the work function in eV or joules, and the light
                as either wavelength (nm or m) or frequency (Hz or THz).
                Internally, all quantities are converted to SI units (joules,
                meters, seconds) for the calculations.
              </p>

              <h3>
                What happens if the photon energy is below the work function?
              </h3>
              <p>
                If \(E_{\text{photon}} &lt; \phi\), then \(K_{\max} \le 0\) and
                no electrons are emitted. The calculator detects this case and
                shows a note that the photoelectric effect does not occur for
                the chosen parameters.
              </p>

              <h3>Can this calculator model photocurrent or intensity?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This tool focuses on the energy side of the photoelectric
                effect: threshold, kinetic energy, stopping potential, and
                electron speed. Photocurrent depends on light intensity, surface
                area, quantum efficiency, and experimental geometry, which are
                beyond the scope of this simple calculator.
              </p>
